<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="503" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,926,2031]" pageId="1" pageNumber="503">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1250,1275]" pageId="1" pageNumber="503">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species is similar to members of 
<emphasis box="[790,919,1251,1275]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="503">shaowuica-</emphasis>
species group by general appearance, which including: 
<taxonomicName authority="Daniel" authorityName="Daniel" authorityYear="1954" box="[271,633,1286,1311]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Microlithosia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="503" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="shaowuica">
<emphasis box="[271,549,1286,1310]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="503">Microlithosia shaowuica</emphasis>
Daniel
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="(de Joannis)" authorityName="de Joannis" baseAuthorityName="de Joannis" baseAuthorityYear="1928" box="[644,969,1286,1311]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Microlithosia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="503" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="umbripuncta">
<emphasis box="[644,824,1286,1310]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="503">M. umbripuncta</emphasis>
(de Joannis)
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Dubatolov, Kishida &amp; Wang. All" authorityName="Dubatolov, Kishida &amp; Wang. All" authorityYear="2012" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Microlithosia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="503" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nanlingica">
<emphasis box="[1027,1184,1286,1310]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="503">M. nanlingica</emphasis>
Dubatolov, Kishida &amp; Wang. All
</taxonomicName>
species of this group have the forewing with a discal and a costal dark spots, and roundly convex costal margin. However, 
<taxonomicName authority="Bayarsaikhan &amp; Lee &amp; Bae, 2018" authorityName="Bayarsaikhan &amp; Lee &amp; Bae" authorityYear="2018" box="[358,484,1358,1382]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Microlithosia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="503" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laosana" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[358,484,1358,1382]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="503">M. laosana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[490,552,1358,1383]" pageId="1" pageNumber="503" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[490,552,1358,1383]" pageId="1" pageNumber="503">n. sp.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
is differs from members by having the slightly convex forewing costal margin, about 1/3 of apex, plus the dark discal and claviform spots, and diffused distal area (
<figureCitation box="[1094,1202,1394,1419]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–3" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1958,1981]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,237,1873]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,237,1873]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–3. Adults of genus Microlithosia spp. form Laos. 1. M. laosana sp. n., holotype, male, Laos. 2. M. umbripuncta, male, Laos. 3. M. nanlingica, male, Laos." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1455405/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="503">Figs. 1–3</figureCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation box="[1214,1356,1394,1419]" pageId="1" pageNumber="503" refId="ref3732" refString="Daniel, F. (1954) Beitrage Zur Kenntnis der Arctiidae Ostasiens under besonderer Beriicksichtingung der Ausbeuten. H. Hones ausdiesens Gebiets Lepidoptera, Heterocera-III, Teil: Lithosiinae. Bonner Zoologische Beitrage, 5 (1 - 2), 89 - 270." type="journal article">Daniel 1954</bibRefCitation>
: 135).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,926,2031]" pageId="1" pageNumber="503">
In male genitalia, all species of 
<emphasis box="[559,688,1430,1454]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="503">shaowuica-</emphasis>
species group have asymmetrical distal and basal saccular process and vesica with field of small spines. On its turn, 
<taxonomicName authority="Bayarsaikhan &amp; Bae" authorityName="Bayarsaikhan &amp; Lee &amp; Bae" authorityYear="2018" box="[718,1091,1466,1491]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Microlithosia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="503" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laosana" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[718,846,1467,1491]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="503">M. laosana</emphasis>
Bayarsaikhan &amp; Bae
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1103,1167,1466,1491]" pageId="1" pageNumber="503" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1103,1167,1466,1491]" pageId="1" pageNumber="503">n. sp.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
presents symmetrically branched distal saccular processes and aedeagus with a bundle of slender spines and field of short spines (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 4–6" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1876,1899]" captionTargetBox="[188,1389,200,1821]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[127,1414,200,1840]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 4–6. Male genitalia of genus Microlithosia spp. from Laos. 4. M. laosana sp. n., Laos (INU˗1846L, holotype). 5. M. umbripuncta, Laos (INU˗1827L). 6. M. nanlingica, Laos (INU˗1819L)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1455407/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="503">Figs. 4– 6</figureCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation box="[180,321,1538,1563]" pageId="1" pageNumber="503" refId="ref3732" refString="Daniel, F. (1954) Beitrage Zur Kenntnis der Arctiidae Ostasiens under besonderer Beriicksichtingung der Ausbeuten. H. Hones ausdiesens Gebiets Lepidoptera, Heterocera-III, Teil: Lithosiinae. Bonner Zoologische Beitrage, 5 (1 - 2), 89 - 270." type="journal article">Daniel 1954</bibRefCitation>
: 135, Abb. 97).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="503" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,926,2031]" pageId="1" pageNumber="503">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1574,1599]" pageId="1" pageNumber="503">Description.</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[351,412,1574,1598]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="503">Adult</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[428,493,1574,1599]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–3" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1958,1981]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,237,1873]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,237,1873]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–3. Adults of genus Microlithosia spp. form Laos. 1. M. laosana sp. n., holotype, male, Laos. 2. M. umbripuncta, male, Laos. 3. M. nanlingica, male, Laos." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1455405/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="503">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Length of forewing 
<quantity box="[744,849,1575,1599]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" metricValueMax="10.0" metricValueMin="8.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="503" unit="mm" value="9.0" valueMax="10.0" valueMin="8.0">8˗10 mm</quantity>
. Head and thorax yellowish brown. Ground color of forewing yellow brownish, costal margin slightly convex about 1/3 of apex, a clear dark discal and a diffuse dark claviform spots; cilia pale yellowish. Hindwing white yellowish; cilia as in forewing. Abdomen pale, with yellowish tuft.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,926,2031]" pageId="1" pageNumber="503">
<emphasis box="[199,368,1718,1742]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="503">Male genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[388,461,1718,1743]" captionStart="FIGURES 4–6" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1876,1899]" captionTargetBox="[188,1389,200,1821]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[127,1414,200,1840]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 4–6. Male genitalia of genus Microlithosia spp. from Laos. 4. M. laosana sp. n., Laos (INU˗1846L, holotype). 5. M. umbripuncta, Laos (INU˗1827L). 6. M. nanlingica, Laos (INU˗1819L)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1455407/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="503">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). Uncus slender, hook-shaped, with small spine at tip, with almost same length of tegumen; cucullus tapering to apex, shark dorsal fin-shaped; distal saccular process slender, curved downwards, with two asymmetric branch, reaching apex of valvae; basal saccular process stout, finger-shaped, bearing stout setae throughout its length, and with an apical spine, left basal saccular process twice longer than right; juxta domeshaped; aedeagus short, stout, with a long medial process; vesica with a bundle of slender spines and field of short spines.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,926,2031]" box="[199,400,1934,1959]" pageId="1" pageNumber="503">Female unknown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
